title: For Sale/Trade:  Join ARMSLIST Flagging Team
postcontent:
If you are tired of seeing inappropriate ads on ARMSLIST join us to keep this site clean and give the boot to all those who really just don’t belong here:

Scammers: A-holes just trying to run a con.
Spammers: Multiple listings for the same firearm.
Overpriced: Ridiculously high-priced items.
Best Offer: Those who think ARMSLIST is auction site, trying to get buyers into a bidding war.
Self-Important Rules: Those who think they can make up their own transfer regulations that supersede state and federal law, such as requiring a  concealed-carry permit to buy a shotgun, or don’t know what a Bill of Sale is (a Bill of Sale is a essentially a glorified receipt and goes to the buyer, not the seller - duh).

To join the ARMSLIST Flagging Team contact us through this posting and include your first name and direct email address and we will add you to the team. Then whenever you see an ad that you feel is inappropriate you send us an email with the ad’s URL (direct web address) and the reason you feel the ad needs to be removed. We will send the posting’s URL out to all members of the flagging team and the ad will be removed! So if you want to help keep ARMSLIST a great place to deal firearms, join us today!

title: For Sale:  Authentic post WWII U.S. Pineapple Fragmentation Grenade
postcontent: This listing is for one practice version of a post WW II U.S. MKII fragmentation grenade which has been rendered inert. This grenade features a M228 fuse again rendered inert and detachable spoon complete with removable ringed pin. The MKIIA1 was first introduced in 1942 and was painted bright yellow, the color code for "High Explosive" After 1943 these grenades were painted drab olive with a yellow band located just under the fuse cap, again identifying these grenades as "High Explosive". This type of grenade was used in Korea and into the Viet Nam war. These grenades can not be re-armed and make the perfect addition to your collection, as well as must have equipment for re-enactors, or simply as a desk ornament for the avid enthusiast.

title: For Sale:  Barrett M82A1 82A1 50 50BMG
postcontent: Here's that big thumper you've been hesitating to buy. It's a lot of money but you want it so bad you can taste it. Well, here it is at a good price. This is the Barrett 82A1 System. The system includes one .50 caliber semi-automatic rifle with a 29", 1 in 15" twist barrel, an airtight/watertight carrying case with wheels, one ten round magazine, a carrying handle, flip-up iron sights, the 1913 accessory rail elevated 27 MOA, detachable adjustable bipod legs, sling attachment points, and a cleaning kit. The retail price on this system is $8900. This is NOT a perfectly refined target 50. This is a battle rifle. Over 5,000 Barretts have been deployed with our troops. Nations around the world employ them. The Boy Scouts use them regularly against enemies foreign and domestic. Ok, ok, so you can't believe everything I say. These rifles are known for their rugged reliability. The chamber is chrome plated and dimensioned for civilian and military ammo. The weapon system is proven. The trigger is appropriate for a battle rifle. It's interesting that this big honker fits in a regular sized carry case. You pull two pins and it disassembles into the upper and lower unit. If you have a scope mounted, it remains mounted on the upper receiver and the zero is maintained. It's thought out and designed for battlefield engagement of material targets to great distances. Perfect for third world soccer games! The assembled rifle is 57" OAL and weighs nearly 31 pounds.  I've done my best. I will be glad to sell anywhere it's legal. Many of us shooters have dreamed of owning the Barrett 82A1. It's something like an ultimate icon. It isn't likely necessary for many of us in our day to day lives. Sometimes we wonder if it might not be useful in the days ahead. But we're absolutely sure that it would be too cool there on the coffee table and out at the range. It definitely comes with braggin' rights. thanks!

title: For Sale:  Mossberg 695 slug gun w/ Leupold 2-7x33
postcontent:
The Mossberg 695 is a bolt action 12 gauge shotgun constructed in North Haven, Connecticut specifically for the task of giving the finger to places that don't allow deer hunting with a rifle.  The 695 has a 22" rifled bore barrel suitable for firing slugs with the range and accuracy of a big game rifle.  This is the hardware you need to reach out 150 yards and earn some sausage during deer season in Iowa.

I've topped this boomstick with a 2-7x33 Leupold VX-II shotgun scope.  It's sighted in and ready to roll.  Optics are what you'd expect from Leupold.  The eye relief for this particular scope is very generous and forgiving.  Box for the scope is included and pictured so you can see the reticle.  Very lightweight combo.

Also comes with camouflage sling, case, and a couple boxes of my favorite 1900 fps 2-3/4" sabot slugs.  The gun can shoot 3" shells in case you want even worse arm-severing recoil but these are what its sighted in with.  The gun holds 2+1 shells so 10 should last you a few seasons unless you're Elmer Fudd.

Everything is in great condition but feel free to come see for yourself or email me with questions.  That doesn't mean its ok to get all "Storage Pickers Stars" on me and waste my time.

Forgive me for the photograph, and my girlfriend's thinly veiled attempt to manipulate the the firearms community through patriotism.  Kick-ass portrait of George Washington not included.
